  Falconi</font><br>
  &nbsp;writer/producer/director/editor</font></div>
<div align="center"> <font size="3" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><br>
  </font> 
  <p align="left" style="display:block; width:80%; line-height:23px;"><font size="3" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">Enrico Falconi was introduced to filmmaking while studying drama and photography at Santa Barbara City College. In 1987, he was cast in the award winning, SBCC, production of Neil Simon’s, Biloxi Blues, and has worked in film, theatre and television, ever since. He received a certificate in film, from New York University’s, Film, Theatre & Broadcasting program in 1996. To date he’s worked on over 50 short and feature films in almost every capacity. In 1995 Enrico worked at the I.F.P. as the shorts screening coordinator for the Independent Feature Film Market in New York. In 1996 & 2006 he curated a film series, the Falcon Film Fiesta. A collection of shorts.

At the age of 27, Enrico found his calling as an auteur with his debut, 20      minute, short, Thinking About Chocolate, (IFFM/96, Albany International Short Film Fest/96, The New Filmmaker’s Forum at the SLIFF/96, Howl Festival 2001). That fall, he was the 2nd assistant director on Darren Aronofsky’s, Pi (Winner - Sundance Film Festival ‘98: Best Director; Independent Spirit Awards ‘99: First Screenplay). (Enrico also had a small role in PI, as one of the Cabala Scholars). In 1999, he co-produced, edited & acted in, Man Woman Film, a $40.000, 16mm, B&W feature film, featuring Cameron Diaz.  Written and directed by Cameron Pearson, it has appeared in over twenty international film festivals and was being considered for participation in the Quinzaine Realisateurs(Director’s Fortnight) at Cannes 2000, only to be disqualified for having already screened around the world. 
Enrico is the author of three screenplays: The Beer run, How Much To Manhattan & Between Days.  He has written, directed, produced and edited 10 short      films: Thinking About Chocolate-1996, 
Angry Jenkins’Farm-2001, Go To Jail-2002, 1937-2002, Original Black Poet-2003, Alsjeblieft-2005, No Turning Back-2006, Brotherly Love-2009, Tequila Sunset-2010, Bella -2011.  He’s currently directing his first feature, Blisster.  An art film about Karma & Timing.  To be premiered in Cannes, 2011.

He is also in his      19th year of filming a documentary: Experience, the Robin Nolan Story."An odyssey through sound, chronicling the life and career of a virtuoso Gypsy jazz guitarist from Amsterdam". 

He is currently writing two screenplays.  A holiday tear jerker with collaborator Cameron Pearson, called The Heart Before Christmas.   And a vampire thriller entitled The Amsterdamned. 

Enrico was raised in the East Village of New York City, where he still lives,      with his cat Max.
</font> </p>
